As a scuba diver, I noticed one error in the video... Fish with swim bladders don't actually let air out to descend.  When they descend, they add air into the swim bladder to maintain neutral buoyancy.  When you ascend, you release air to maintain neutral buoyancy. It is counter-intuitive, but you just need to maintain the same volume of air, so as you descend, the air is compressed and you need to add air to maintain the same volume and vice-versa. I don't understand why people, especially science-minded ones, suggest that pressure/depth affects anything made of liquid or solid, and therefore they must have certain characteristics to "withstand" it from being crushed. Liquids and solids are nearly incompressible. Pressure and material characteristics are only important together when there is a pressure difference , which can cause an actual strain on the material. This is why spongy paper cartridge filters in the pressure-side of hydraulic machinery are unaffected by pressure, even though their container is made of thick steel. There's nowhere for it to go into.

Put bone and flesh, without any air pockets, in a pressure vessel, charge it to 60,000 psi, then drain the pressure, and it will have been completely unaffected. The exception is bone which has air trapped inside, which most terrestrial bone has, which would be crushed, but only until the air itself is crushed, no further. The solid bone material itself wouldn't be affected.

I'd be happy to explain away any further doubts about this 👍
